segments.text: And then we paid him back.
And that was sort of symbolic of the community as it was in those days.
Was there any place that was kind of off limits?
Was Uncle Ed's still going?
Uncle Ed's was still going.
It wasn't off limits.
It was a pretty going place.
Uncle Ed's was torn down.
I guess it was my end of my junior year.
It must have been the end of my junior year.
So that would have been in not going.
to be sure I hadn't taken it over.
And it was still going until about your junior year?
I think they tore it down the end of my junior year.
I can't remember for sure.
The reason I know it was during my time here is we had a crepper ceremony for it.
Do you know what a crepper ceremony was?
Describe.
This was really oriented around people who got a Dear John letter.
And there were a lot of those in those days.
Typically you'd come here as a freshman and you'd have a high school girlfriend and somewhere along that fall semester you'd get the letter.
And we had a little ceremony.

uh and in the ceremony you would all dress up in your raincoats and ponchos i mean ponchos and pots and you would carry brooms and you would mourn your way through the halls of the then you would go in you would all the entire outfit would crowd into one of the gang restrooms and the
person that was being affected was called to the center and the letter was read to everyone and then it was torn up and put into the crapper there were there were four no there were five uh

uh sit down crappers and then two urinals making seven and you had a 21 crapper salute there were people stationed at each one and you would sprinkle a letter around and you would flush it and then of course you would make your way back to your room and that well we had one of those for uncle ed's when it was torn down it was pretty tragic thing and so we we had a crapper sermon
All right, now during that day, if someone wanted to just go drink some beer, where did they go?
Most of the time, like as a freshman and sophomore, you would go to the river.
You'd find somebody, you'd get a couple of cases, or not cases, but kegs.
You'd go out and find a place on the Brazos River where it was safe and away from everything.
And then you'd swim in the river and drink and play games.

it was just common and was generally all male all male absolutely then if you if someone wanted to drink hard liquor i mean drink whiskey yeah well it wasn't a lot of that that went on but you went to whiskey you had to go to whiskey bridge obviously to get it and there was it wasn't that hard to buy i had a
A fellow that was a senior in my outfit when I was a freshman, he was an ag engineer and had a drawing table in his room.
Name was Jerry Simpton.
Jerry is the president of the bank in Del Rio today and would deny this, I'm sure.
But Jerry had a side business which was converting your driver's license to one showing that you were 21 years of age or older.
And it was, in those days, the driver's license was paper.
And he would pin it to his drawing board and very adroitly cut out the right numbers and switch them, and then laminate the driver's license.
And it was quite a talent.
He was very good at it.
So there were several people that had a driver's license that allowed you to.
And of course, the folks that were selling the liquor would wink, and it really wasn't a big problem.
By the time I was an upperclassman, there were a few places around.
Uncle Ed's was a place you drank beer and ate barbecue.
Martin's, a place called Eastgate Lounge, which was just a little bar.
And then there were some places in North Bryan, which probably a person wouldn't go to today.
But in those days, Highway 21 from downtown Bryan headed west, there were probably a half a dozen just
who to hell places that you could go and drink beer and listen to jukebox.
Let's go back to your being Corps Commander.
You get here in the fall.
Did anyone give you a kind of a guideline or responsibility as a set of goals or anything?
Not really.
I mean, that was pretty much ours to develop, although Colonel Baker, who was the commandant, was...
I mentioned a couple of things a while ago.
Also, just fundamental discipline and harassment and that sort of thing was difficult to control in those days.
And he had a major concern, which was an appropriate one, about the rate of departure of kids coming in here.
So one of the things we worked very hard on starting the year was to try to retain as many as possible, and with some success.
And we had a really good group of commanders that year.
A guy named Pat Gamble, who's a four-star in the Air Force, was commander of one of the Air Force wings.
Arturo Esquivel, who was commander of the Air Division, which was the senior Air Force commander, and a couple of guys on the Army side that were just outstanding.
So we had good solid, not to any surprise to you, good leadership selected.
But what was the Corps enrollment then?
Do you remember?
We started that fall probably close to 3,000.
And by the end of the year, we were probably down to
Oh, somewhere around 25, 2600 would be my guess.
So it was, you know, it was already down significantly.
As the fall semester got underway, what was the daily routine for the weekday for the corps commander?
Not sure I can remember.
It was long days, that's all I remember.
I had a deputy corps commander named Robert Bean who was an electrical engineer, had been on corps staff, very, very bright guy.

The thing I remember about Robert is he was so disciplined that he would go to class and then come home every night at the end of the day, no matter what the hour, and recopy his notes such that you could read them.
It was almost like reading a typewriter.
I was not that disciplined, at least as a scholar.
But Robert, the reason I mention Robert is that Robert got up every morning and went to breakfast.
So he was one of those guys we could always depend on.
If the whole staff wasn't going, he was always there.
But typically you got up, you started early, got to chow, and then by the time I got to my senior year, I had a light load.
I only had 15 hours each semester.
And unlike my early years where I had a lot of lab classes, I didn't have as many labs.
Mostly I had liberal arts and journalism classes my senior year.
So it was a little bit easier to manage through.
But I probably didn't go to class a lot.
I spent a lot of time in the Commandant's office, in Hannigan's office, President Rutter's office, and in dealing with leadership activities of the Corps.
Did you eat most of your three meals a day in the dining hall?
Yeah, for the most part.
I mean, by the time you got to be a senior, you were getting a little tired of the Duncan Hall chow.
And so you would, especially in the spring, you would find ways to slide off campus in the evenings a lot of the time and grab a meal.
But for the most part, it was, and you were in formation, so you were, you know, you were actually commanding the evening and noon and morning formations.
All right, and it was expected that you as Corps commander be present for all three of those formations.
Well, for the most part.
I wasn't there for all of them.
But, I mean, you always had someone.
If you weren't, you had to make sure there was somebody to stand in and...

take the review as you look on that back on that year what are the most positive events you recall well i think it was for me again a small town country boy it was sort of the awakening to a bigger world you know i remember for example i was the student host of edward teller
the infamous creator of the, I guess, the hydrogen bomb.
And he was here for Great Issues or SCONA or one of those events.
And I was the, and you know, I mean, this was to me a pretty sobering thought.
And just being involved in essentially, to a great degree, managing the institution from a student standpoint.
It was, again, a real eye opening.
I don't know, you don't go from being a small town country boy one day to being a cosmopolitan, urbane person the next, but it was this
it was probably as profound a changing experience for me as I could ever have.

Still having, you know, plenty of fun and camaraderie and, you know, being around friends and doing student things, but it was, you know, you became a, you really became a grown-up in real ways during that year.
One of the interesting negatives is that

a reminder again, we were in the Vietnam era, so there was sort of a, I didn't think about it so much at the time because it was sick humor or it was just a way to survive it because the stories ran through the dormitory about people that you knew that were there and what was happening to them and the forecasted life expectancy of a second lieutenant in battle and that kind of thing.
But there was a bit of a pall
on the Corps in those days, because the expectation was.
And sort of a theme song was, what the hell are they gonna do, send me to Vietnam?
I mean, everybody knew.
The minute you got your commission and as soon as you got through with a bit of orientation training in the Army, you were going.
So it was a,

interesting and maturing time but also a very sobering and uh sort of uh uh you know strange time around the place i asked this one with this great face what kind of protest anti-war protest did y'all have to cope with the one i remember best was i remember i told you about that summer that my friend and i stayed here well the word filtered through the dorms that there was a
SDS organizer from Austin coming to the campus and that wanted to be sure everybody in the dorms knew this was happening.
You know, sort of implying that we would all want to go out and hear what he had to say.
Well, sure enough, the guy did show up and he was at Hensel Park and that old strange looking white pavilion thing that was built over there.
He got about three or four words out of his mouth
and all of a sudden he was on the tops of a set of thousand hands being literally carried to the city limits.
I will to this day believe that probably either Earl Rudder or Hannigan or Bob Melcher, who was sort of a, Bob was a guy of some intrigue, had gotten the word out about this organizer coming
and knew exactly what would happen.
Because the place was very, you know, we were completely out of sync with what was happening in the rest of the world.
I can remember sitting in my dorm room and hearing I Want to Hold Your Hand sung by the Beatles the first time.
That was in 63 or 64.
By the time I got to be a senior in the corps, the rest of the world were smoking dope and wearing flowers in their hair.
We didn't even see it, hardly.
On the matter of drugs, were you aware of any A&M kids smoking anything?
Never.
Never smelled the stuff until I got to Vietnam.
Did, were you and your buddies even aware of the words cocaine?
No.
And crack?
No.
You know, a heroin addict was someone who was the absolute lowest depths of society.
And actually my wife,
North Texas was a party school in those days, and my wife became aware of the marijuana stuff while she was up there.
But I never knew about it, other than just what you might read or see.
During that year as court commander, did you have to cope with any tragedies here?
One of the, you know, this is, I'll tell you a little bit about how much the place has changed.
We had a fella named Sammy Green, who I believe was the first black to be commissioned from A&M.
And Sammy came into the Corps as a junior, I think.
Sammy was not the brightest bulb and not the best soldier, and as a result,
That plus his race, he kept being harassed.
And it was in good humor, but it wasn't.
I mean, it was because, I mean, here's one of the first minorities other than Hispanic.
Hispanics were widely accepted in a part of the core culture.
Blacks were not.
But Rutter called me one day and called me over to his office, and he was...
My senior year, I had a phone in the room because I was corps commander.
And when it rang, I usually knew who was calling.
And he didn't go through the chain of command.
The chain of command was Rutter to Davis.
Cadet Davis, come to my, or Eddie Joe, I don't know what he said.
Come to my office.
Yes, sir.
So I show up.
And he tells me that Cadet Green has been found on the courthouse lawn
I'm trying to remember where it was.
It was either Brenham or Navasota or I guess Independence.
Not Independence, but Anderson was the county seat.
Well, that is close, you know, tied to the flagpole and, again, quote in good humor.
But he did say to me, if it happens again, I'm going to start with you, and we're going to wipe them out until we get down to wherever it is that this is happening.
I mean, it was very plain and clear.
So we had a little meeting of all the commanders and made it clear that Cadet Green was not going to be hauled off in his birthday suit again and treated this way.
That's sort of one of the kinds of things.
And that one.
Did it work?
Yeah, we didn't.
Again, Sammy was a guy that didn't have a lot to offer, but he was there, and as a result of all that, he finally made it through and I think got commissioned.
I'm almost sure he did.
But we didn't have any more incidents that I knew of.
We probably had a few more.
I don't remember any other particular tragedies.
We had a lot of...

again, controversy between the civilian students and the Corps, had a good friend named Heaton, a nephew of the infamous Heaton that was the registrar, who was the civilian student, whatever we called it, president of the civilian student body.
And he and I were friends and had been friends for a long time, and so it was
One of the things we worked on a lot was that relationship and trying to improve it.
And I think that paid off throughout the year.
What was it like to be the Corps commander for a Corps trip?
Well, now that was really magic.
I mean, you think about...
staring down the streets of Congress Avenue, or in the case of Dallas, I guess it was Maine or Elm, I don't remember.
But to lead the Corps cadets on a major Corps trip was quite a... How did you feel?
Oh, you tingled all over.
And how were Aggies treated by the observers?
You know, the people were...
The people that turned out for that Corps trip, and there were a lot of them in those days.
I had an old aunt from Wichita Falls who was really a great, great aunt.
And she came, she drove with her husband in a big Chrysler all the way from Wichita Falls to Dallas to see Eddie Joe lead the Corps of Cadets.
And it was, you know, I mean, you had that coming from all over the state.
And then the people that were locals would turn up.
Where did you stay?
Do you remember?
I believe at the Adolphus.
All right.
And all the members of the Corps paid for their own accommodations?
You just found your own way.
There was no organization to it except where you showed up, the place to arrive and begin the parade.
I don't remember for sure, but I believe the Adolphus by that time was kind of a rundown old hotel in Dallas.
And there was a court trip party at the Adolphus.
So I think that's where I stayed.
And the marches began at 10 o'clock or so?
Yeah, it depends on when the game was.
But in those days, most of the games were standard time, like 2 o'clock in the afternoon.
So the parade would have started at 9 or 10 in the morning.
Describe Earl Rudder as you saw him as corps commander.
You know, it's hard for me to do that without reflecting on what I know about him now.
And before I talk about Rutter, I want to talk about Hannigan a little bit.
Because Jim Hannigan was a guy that we all, you know, if you ever went to Hannigan's office, it was too late.
you were on your way out, or you were maybe out of the Corps, because it all got dealt with pretty much before you got to him.
And as a result of that,
Hannigan was feared and was viewed as a, oh I don't know, sort of a stoic, tough general.
I got to know him as I came back to work here not long after being a student, five years
and he was one of the kindest, gentlest, most down to earth guys I've ever known.
And I dearly developed a great admiration for him, but never did that as a student because I didn't see that side of him.
Rutter a lot the same way I would guess.
Rutter was a
again a guy that was very firm, very, he had a sense of humor, but it wasn't easy as a cadet to, you know, find it.
I remember my interview with him.
when this was, you know the selections basically had been made by everybody and he had to be the final check off.
So I go up to his office, Nelda Green, my old friend was then Nelda Rowell, was in an office that I would later occupy as deputy chancellor.
But you know, you keep your nose clean and in a few years you make good.
But anyway, Nelda always made you feel comfortable and sort of warm and nice.
And I went into his office, and he was still on the phone.
She took me in, and she just said, sit down.
And so he pointed at the chair.
And he got off the phone, and he stood up, shook hands, and he said, Eddie Joe, you've been recommended to be the corps commander.
He said, you're a fine looking young man.
I just have one question for you.
And I said, yes, sir.
What's that, Mr. Rutter?
He said, are you tough enough?
Pretty tough question for a 20-year-old cadet.
And I said, well, Mr. Rutter, I'm as tough as I need to be.
Whatever it takes to get the job done, I'll do.
He said, that's all I need to hear.
And then we chit-chatted, talked about a lot of things that were going on.
And he was warm and friendly and very much enjoyed it.
I've had some other occasions when
I was called to his office.
It wasn't so warm and friendly.
During that year?
No, no, that was my junior year.
No, no, no, but during your year as Corps Commander.
Oh, absolutely.
Sammy Green would have been an example.
I mean, there wasn't any question.
I mean, it was clear when I left there what I had to do.
And, you know, he made it clear.
And as I said, chain of command was not in his vocabulary.
If there was an issue going on with the Corps, now he would obviously
Denzel Baker, the commandant, would know about it and was involved in it, but he fired that shot right down to the corner room in dorm two and expected me to take care of it.
If you needed any advice about how to respond to one of his, to whom did you turn?
Well, there were a couple of places.
There were two guys in the commandant's office in those days.
One was a guy named Ken Nicholas.
Frank
K, I guess, but went by Nick.
He was a retired sergeant major from the Army and stayed on there as sort of an administrative assistant or whatever.
And Nick was a guy that you could go close the door and sit down and talk to.
And there was another guy named Lieutenant Colonel Brooks, who I don't remember whether he was an active duty officer or a reservist, but he likewise was a guy
If you got in a box and you didn't want to go talk to Denzel Baker because you knew you probably would be in the box with him, you go talk to one of those two guys, they'd give you good advice.
So that was, and there were a few other places around the campus in those days.
Joe Buser was, I guess, editor of the Texas Aggie, and Buck Wirus was the Association of Former Students head.

And Ed Cooper was the assistant to the president, and you know on sort of campus politics issues and things like that that were testy, I could go sit down with one of those guys and get some pretty good advice.
I remember Buser and Wiris both
probably pulled my fat out of the fire a number of times.
Now, interestingly, and this might surprise you a little bit, but Wayne Stark was not one of my real mentors or confidants.
Wayne was a guy who, Wayne was very good at picking people out and sort of saying, you know, I think he's got the stuff.
And I was one of those.
But Wayne had done a thing or two that didn't sit well with me.
One was he criticized one of my best friends about deciding to marry a girl and said that she was beneath him.
And, you know, this was really not.
But you knew Wayne well enough to know that he would be that straightforward and honest.
But he was not a guy that I would go sit down with necessarily.
and share with.
Later, after I left, as I said, he dogged me until I finally agreed to apply to go to business school.
And I have a very high regard for him, but he was not one that, Dick Potts was another guy that I could always trust to get good advice from.
would not let me out of Genetics 301, but he did give me good advice.
And there were probably a number of others that I just, that don't come to mind.
But around the campus,
There were always a lot of, in those days, and they were mostly faculty, some involved in student organizations, but mostly faculty that you could always call on to get good advice.
Now, the Corps commander in those days got no compensation, did he?
No scholarship?
No, no, no.
There was a
Commander's pay, I think it was $10 a month.
What you got there was for handing out the keys and taking up the keys and making sure people's room was sandwiched, whatever all that was.
There was a little sweetener to your pay.
Was there any good bull prank played on you by your old buddies when they learned you'd been selected as Corps Commander?
Oh, yes.
Describe it.
We have to do this on tape.
If it is tapeable.
Well, I lived in the Speza area my junior year, so we were at Chow, and announcements were made, and it was announced who the new corps commander was gonna be.
Well, I was on the tops of a lot of hands on my way to the fish pond, thrown in the fish pond, and then taken back to my dorm, and we had a ceremony that's rather,
Byzantine now, but they shaved you in places that you shouldn't be shaved, which made it very uncomfortable at summer camp.
But that was the ritual.
And as far as you knew, you were not the first one?
Oh, heavens no.
To have that?
And for reasons of survival, you were very still.
Let's see.
I'm now looking at campus activities and so forth.
Was Guyon Hall still an important place for

Yeah, you know, you went there to watch We've Never Been Licked, and you went there for major assemblies, like the Bevo Assembly, and the first one you first got to school, you know, to be told nobody would be left when you got through.
Yeah, it was a place.
It was pretty craggy in those days.

They used to have the Cotton Pageant, which was a big event, you know, where women would be imported from various places around the state and be candidates for the Cotton Queen, I think is what it was called.

So that was, and you know, usually as a student in agriculture, you were involved even early on in that and hosting people and trying to get lucky enough to find one of those pretty ones to, you know, escort.
Now you met this special young lady when you were a junior?
Junior.
And when she came down here, where did she spend the night?
Where did she stay?
Well, you know, that first trip I don't even remember.
I think maybe she might have stayed with her parents in Marlin, you know, gone back to Marlin.
The second trip, though, I invited her at the end of that visit to come back for the combat and military ball weekend.
and she stayed at the Sabre Motel.
I had two guys, two fish in my outfit, Fish Harvey and Fish Mac Frazier, who played the guitar
and sang to come over and be in the room when she arrived to serenade her.
And she still, they still, and she still remembers that event.
All right, now this sounds like that you began to feel this was serious pretty quickly.
Well, she was pretty special.
You know, and I was trying to save her from all those strange people up in North Texas.
There you go, there you go.
Her brother was an Aggie, class of 62, and he was a little worried about her as well.
And when he found out she had a date with an Aggie, he was encouraging.
How were young women at an A&M social event, a dance or a football game, in fact, how were they treated by Aggies?
I would say they were treated like princesses, which is just the way you would expect to be treated.
having not seen it from that side it's hard for me to imagine but it must have been a wonderful experience for a young woman to come here and be

see all these guys in uniforms which we saw every day but to them it must have been quite special and you know just being treated and you always had a corsage you always you know you put on the dog and you did everything you could do within reason and brand college station to make them feel special and welcome if i were to ask your wife about how she felt they were treated do you think she would concur
